@Node "Options" "DunderDir.Guide/Options"

OPTIONS:
   Usage: DD [{File | Dir | Options}]

 The options are case-sensitive and may be entered anyware
 in the command line. You can specify upto 35 pathes to
 list if you feel like it 8-)


  OPTION :  WHAT IT DOES
  ----------------------

     a   : This will list the directory and all
           it's subdirectorys.

     A   : This is like -a but it takes no care
           of patterns and other options.

           Ex. DD -Af DH1:#?.asm

           This will go through all dirs in dir DH1:
           and onley print files ending with .asm.
           But with -a the dirs must end with .asm
           or they would not be entered.

     B   : Display onley files with a specifyed
           size. This option also works on dirs
           if -g(se below) was specifyed. The
           size must stand right next to the
           option. Ex. DD -Bs500000

      Bb : Show files with blocksize <= <blocksize>
      BB : Show files with blocksize >= <blocksize>
      Bs : Show files with bytesize  <= <bytesize>
      BS : Show files with bytesize  >= <bytesize>

     c   : Display files/dirs in columns. Default
           number of columns is 4. But you may
           select between 3 - 15. If it's not a
           number or the number is below 3 it
           will be treated as an option. The number
           must stand right next to the option..
           Ex. DD -c5

     C   : The file comments(if any) will not be
           displayed on screen.

     d   : Onley directorys will be displayed.

     D   : Display dirs and files like DIR but
           also showing the sizes for the files.

     E   : If this is used the LFormat string will
           be executed instead of printed. This option
           has no effect unless the -L option is used.
           NOTE: This option is very slow at this
                 moment(on my 68000 it is).

     f   : Onley files will be displayed.

     F   : Choose what date you want to use.
           Default is AmigaDOS(dd-mmm-yy) format.

      Fa : American         (mm-dd-yy).
      Fc : Canadian         (dd-mm-yy).
      Fi : International   (yy-mmm-dd).

     g   : Get size for a dir. This option enters
           the dir and count all files sizes for
           the dir. This can take a while if the
           dir contains many files and subdirectorys.

     h   : Don't display files where h bit
           is set.

     H   : Don't display files that starts
           with a dot.

     i   : No .info files will be displayed.

     I   : Ignore patterns. Ex. DD -I *.*
           Then DD will be forced to belive that
           *.* is a file and will not list a whole
           dir searching for files/dirs that match.

     k   : Shows the diskkey for files/dirs.

     l   : This will put the dirs last.
           The -D option ignore this.

     L   : For use of a LFormat string.
           All LISTS lformat options are supported.

            %A - Attributes(the file protection bits).
            %B - Size in blocks.
            %C - The files comment(if any).
            %D - The files creation date.
            %E - The files extension.
                 Ex. WildChange.asm = asm

            %F - The whole path to the file/dir name.
            %K - The file/dirs diskkey.
            %L - The size in bytes.
            %M - The name without the extension.
                 Ex. WildChange.asm = WildChange

            %N - The file/dir name.
            %P - The path from the current directory.
            %S - This option is different then LISTS.
                 This is the same as typing %F%N.
            %T - The time of the creation date.

           You may also write the length of the name
           Ex. %-25N. Also C like string options is
           supported. Some i don't think you'll ever
           use :)  Here are the list..

             \" - *"  : "
             \\ -     : \
             \* - **  : *
                - *e  : Esc
                                      ASCII
             \a -     : Flash screen    $7
             \b -     : BackSpace       $8
             \f -     : Clear Screen    $c
             \n - *n  : ENTER           $a
             \t -     : Horizontal tab  $9
             \v -     : Vertical tab    $b

         Everything is case-insensitive, meaning \n is the
         same as \N and %a the same as %A. If you type a
         misscorrect option it will be ignored.

         NOTE: When using this options -v and -V(se below)
               will also be used. -V because no vars will
               be used anyway, and -v so all files will be
               used. But if you want them to work you can
               specify them again after the -L option.

     m   : Mixes the files and dirs.

     N   : Don't show head, tail and total.

     O   : Will onley show files that got a comment.

     p   : Force DD to pause and wait for users response
           before continue when reached bottom line of the
           CLI/Shell window. You got some options...

              B - Break(Same as pressing Ctrl+C).
              N - Continue without any more breaks.
              S - Step youself down the list by showing
                  the enries one by one.

           NOTE: This option is not finished yet. Because
                 of some BIG changes in the writing routine
                 in v1.04.5 and v1.04.6. It onley works with
                 the options -c, -q and -D. But even then it
                 will not work very correct :(  Because of that
                 it's best to not use this options at all.

     q   : Shows onley the name. Dirs will
           get a slash last in the name.

     r   : This option clears the screen before
           printing the entries =)

     s   : List files/dirs since this date.
           You may use like Today, yesterday
           or any AmigaDOS supported date.

     S   : Choose what you want to sort after.
           Default is after names.

      Sc : Sort after comments.
      Sd : Sort after dates.
      Sk : Sort after diskkey.
      Sn : Then the files/dirs will not be sorted.
      Sr : The sorting will be reversed.
      Ss : Sort by sizes, dirs will sorted after
           there names except if -g was specified.

     t   : Some dates you see like Today, Yesterday...
           but with this option you will se the
           real date for the file/dir.

     u   : List files/dirs upto this date.
           You may use like Today, yesterday
           or any AmigaDOS supported date.

     v   : Will make DD to ignore the use of
           the DDOpts variabel.

     V   : DD will ignore all variables and print
           the defaults. DDOpts is not ignored and
           must be turned of with the -v option.

     w   : Choose the width for the columns. Between
           5 - 35 may be entered. Default is 18. -w must
           be put BEFORE -c or the result may not be correct.
           The number must stand right next to the option.
           Ex. -w15

     -   : When this is specifyed, all other "-" will be
           treated as a file/dir to list.

           Ex1: DD --Ch -afile -hi c:
                    SAME AS
           Ex2: DD -Ch -- -afile -hi c:

           "-afile" and "-hi" will be treated as c:
           and --Ch is treated as normal =)

@EndNode

@Node "Links" "DunderDir.Guide/Links"

LINKS:
 Links are displayed like any file or dir
 except that the name is in bold or italic.

  Hardlinks are displayed in bold.
  Softlinks are displayed in italic.

 You may select the color yourself if you
 would like that. Se @{"variables" Link Variables} for more information.

@EndNode

@Node "Variables" "DunderDir.Guide/Variables"

VARIABLES:

 There are many variables you can use. You may format
 the output in all of these variables like in the -L
 option(if nothing else is said).
  These options may be global or local. DD first look
 for the local and then for the global 8)

 For beginners. Go @{"here" Link Beginners} to learn more
 of how to make a variable and saving them.


   You may use this option in all variables..
     %% - %
   All options are case-insensitive, meaning
   %A and %a is the same.


 NAME: DDHead
   This variable is the text written before the list of
   files/dirs will be displayed.

      %D - Current date
      %T - Current time
      %Y - Current day
      %N - Path to directory from current dir
      %M - Path to directory
      %V - Name of volume listing
      %L - Free disk space in bytes
      %O - Free disk space in blocks


 NAME: DDTail
   This variable is the text written after the list of
   files/dirs has been written. All of the options in
   "DDHead" is used + these. If you use these options in
   the "DDHead" variable then all you'll get is zero.

 NOTE:
   This var will not be used when using -q, -c or -D.

      %I - Number of dirs
      %F - Number of files
      %H - Number of hidden files/dirs. A hidden file is
           a file that is not showed because of the options
           -h, -H and -i. See @{"options" Link Options} for more information
           about the opts.

      %E - Total number of files and dirs. Note that the
           hidden files is not counted.
      %B - Size of all files in bytes.
      %S - Size of all files in blocks.


 NAME: DDTot
   Used when user used option -a or -A. It uses the same
   options as DDTail but they mean the total of everyting.
   It also uses the options in DDHead.

 NOTE:
   This var will not be used when using -D.


 NAME: DDNoEntry
   This var is printed whenever the dir you where listing
   was empty. It uses all the options DDHead and DDTail
   uses. DDHead and DDTail will not be printed.


 NAME: DDOpts
   You may not use -L formating with this variable because
   you would onley get some errormessages. This var is used
   to set some options you would like to have as default.
   Ex. You never want to see the files with the -h bit set
   and files ending with .info. You just type like..

      SetEnv DDOpts -hi

   You also can specify a directory to list here if you want to.
   But i guess you never will use that(i don't) because everytime
   you list a directory you will see this one first.
   If you use this var you should check out the extra program
   Opt that followed with this archive.


 NAME: DDDir
   This var will be used when you don't use -D, -q or -c.
   It will onley work on directorys.

      %A - Attributs(the files protection bits).
      %D - Date dir was created.
      %F - The whole path to the dir.
      %K - Where to put in the DDKey var.
      %N - The name of the dir.
      %P - The path to the dir from the current dir.
      %T - Time dir was created.


 NAME: DDFile
   This var will be used when you don't use -D, -q or -c.
   It will onley work on files. All options in DDDir is
   used + these...

      %B - Size in blocks.
      %C - Where the DDComment will be inserted.
      %L - Size in bytes.

   Using these options with the DDDir var will onely
   give you the result 0 except %C that will result
   of nothing.


 NAME: DDComment
   Whats in this variable will be inserted in the DDFile
   var whenever there are a comment and DDFile/%c is used.

      %C - The comment.


 NAME: DDKDir
   Uses the same options as DDDir, but this var will
   onley be used when you used -k option.


 NAME: DDKFile
   Uses the same options as DDFile, but this var will
   onley be used when you used -k option.


 NAME: DDGDir
   Uses the same options as DDFile except it's option %c.
   This var will be used whenever -g was specifyed.


 NAME: DDGKDir
   Uses the same options as DDFile excepts it's option %c.
   This var will be used whenever -g and -k was specifyed.


 NAME: DDHLink
   Whats in this var will be inserted before "%N" whenever
   there is a hardlink. This is great because you mayby want
   to insert a color so you fast can see that the file/dir
   is a hardlink :)


 NAME: DDSLink
   This is like DDHLink, except that this is for softlinks.



 NOTE:
   Somethimes you will get a incorrect answer when using
   \". But this onley happens when you has qouted the string.

   Ex.  SetEnv DDHead "Diring \"%p\" at %d.\n"
                               *

   Then the dos.library/ReadArgs() function thinks that the
   end of the row is where the star is. This happens because
   the ReadArgs() function(that all of commodores dos program
   uses) is not programed to recognise a \" but a *" works fine.

   But with "Set" and "SetEnv" you don't need to quoute the
   name at all, so this should not be a problem :)

@EndNode

@Node "Beginners" "DunderDir.Guide/Variables/Beginners"

  This is ONLEY for beginners(lamers =) ).

  There are two kind of variables, global and local.
  The local is for use of the CLI window you set it
  in, but a global is for all CLI windows that you
  got(or may) open on screen.

  You use "SetEnv" to set a global var and "Set" for
  a local. Here is an example...

    Global decleration
 SetEnv DDHead Volume "%v"\n

   This will set a global var with the name "DDHead"
   that will contain the value `Volume "%v"\n`.

    Local decleration
 Set DDTail Finished diring "%m"\n

   This will set a local var with the name "DDTail"
   that will contain teh value `Finished diring "%m"\n`.


 Set should onley be used as a temporary variable because
 they can not be saved until next time you turn on your
 Amiga or reboot in an easy way. But to save your global
 variables you just type...

   Copy Env:DD#? EnvArc:


 To delete the variables use "UnSet" and "UnSetEnv"
 To delete a saved one you must type like...

   Delete EnvArc:<name>
   UnSetEnv <name>

 where <name> is the name of the variable you
 want to delete. 


 =) Hope you did understand all =)

@EndNode

@Node "Examples" "DunderDir.Guide/Examples"

   Add this to your S:User-Startup so AmigaDOS don't
   have to load DD every time you want to list a dir.

   Resident C:DD PURE


     Here are some demostrations of how to use DunderDir.
     ----------------------------------------------------

 EXAMPLE 1:
   This is onley an example of you can use DD.


   DD -t -f -C -Sd -u yesterday -s monday sys:c/s#?
         OR
   DD -tfCSdu "yesterday" -s monday sys:c/s#?
         OR
   DD -tfCSdu yesterday sys:c/s#? -s monday
         OR
   DD -C sys:c/s#? -ft -Sd -s"monday"-uyesterday


   All of the above lines work the same.
   Se @{"options" Link Options} if you want to know what
   the options do.

 EXAMPLE 2:

   If you are like me and never uses the
   Workbench, you sometimes want to delete
   all .info when you unpacked a new program.
   To delete all .info files in it's dir and
   all it's subdirs you just type like...

   DD -EAL "Delete \"%s\"" #?.info

   After this all of the .info files will be gone :)

 EXAMPLE 3:

   If you like the program "ls" and want a very simylar
   output you just need to set the variables...

      SetEnv DDDir  "d%a %7b %8l %-9d %n\n"
      SetEnv DDFile "-%a %7b %8l %-9d %n\n"
      SetEnv DDHead ""
      SetEnv DDTail "Dirs:%-4i Files:%-4f Blocks:%-5b Bytes:%s\n"

   When you set these variables as shown above, you will
   get something that looks like "ls" with -l option set
   (-l = long listing).

 EXAMPLE 4:
   Or if you like the "list"s output, set like this...

      SetEnv DDDir  "%-28n Dir %a %-9d %t\n"
      SetEnv DDFile "%-24n %7l %a %-9d %t\n"
      SetEnv DDHead "Directory *"%n*" on %y %d\n"
      SetEnv DDTail "%f files - %i directories - %b blocks used\n"
      SetEnv DDOpts "-m"

   If you set the these variables exactly like this, the onley
   different will be that the files and drawers are sorted :)
   but this can be fixed by seting the "DDOpts" var to "-mSn"
   But who wants it unsorted !? :(

@EndNode

@Node "Systemreq" "DunderDir.Guide/SystemReq"

SYSTEM REQUIREMENTS:

 DunderDir should run on any Amiga with at least kickstart 2.04.
 It has been successfully tested on the following configurations:

 A600  : 2 Mb CHIP,  - Mb FAST, Kickstart 2.04
 A600  : 1 Mb CHIP,  2 Mb FAST, Kickstart 2.04

@EndNode

